logies. Yet in spite of the growing emphasis on security, few truly consider the spatial dimensions of security, and particularly how the relationship between space and security varies across cultures. This volume explores spaces of security not only by attending to how security is produced by and in spaces, but also by emphasizing the ways in which it is constructed in the contemporary landscape. The book explores diverse contexts ranging from biometrics in India to counterterrorism in East Africa to border security in Argentina. The ethnographic studies demonstrate the power of a spatial lens to highlight aspects of security that otherwise remain hidden, while also adding clarity to an elusive and dangerous way of managing the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aInternal securityxSocial aspectsvCase studies. 0aSecurity sectorxSocial aspectsvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aGuam.  aIndia.  aIsrael.  aKenya.  aNairobi.  aRomania.  aSocial Security.  aSouth Africa.  aWar on Drugs.  aWar on Terror.  aanthropology.  aarchitecture.  aassemblage.  aastrogeopolitics.  abiometric state.  aborderization.  acounterterrorism.  acritical events.  aemergency.  agated communities.  ageopolitics.  agovernance.  ahealth insurance.  ahousing.  ainsecurity.  alocal environment.  amamad.  amilitary maps.  aoverseas bases.  apublic security.  arecursiveness.  aresidential space.  aroutine.  asatellites.  asecret police.  asecuritization.  asecurity regimes.  asecurity technology.  asecurity urbanism.  asurveillance.  aurban space.1 aBird-David, Nurit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlück, Zoltán, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Ste